column5: I always wondered why they put so much engineering into a one use item?
hippie
you better give those guys on Canadian Pickers a call if you got more stuff to get rid of. might make a buck or two

Anyone have any clue what this item is?  It's been in my garage for years now (12) and was in my grand parents garage since I can remember.  Made in England, has air connections and gas burner and a gas type connection.  Here is the complete item all together    Here is the base with a burner in it    Inside Base showing burner    Here is the inside portion, top removed and pulled out of the base    Close up of the gauge    Another gauge shot    Thanks for any info on it...  Sherriff
Steralizing device perhaps?
my guess would be and old style tiger torch !?

Like an industrial pressure cooker. The burner heats the liquid or material inside. The big valve on top locks down the lid and the pressure can be observed using the guage. My guess is the air hook-ups allow for safe release of the pressure? Any chance it was off of a train..or from a factory? Looks like a piece to a much bigger machine.
something to produce and collect steam for a clothing manufacturer's press or a cleaning company?
I think Pikeslayer has it.  Thanks.  Either an Autoclave or a Steam Digester for sterilizing.  Possibly dental equipment.  Now, trying to find a similar picture online to date it..    Sherriff
Vul. Point- Vulcanising Point - some sort of pressure cooker for vulcanising rubber. That is my guess.
http://www.imagestate.com/Preview/PreviewPage.aspx?id=2197145    Sherriff
Is there a prize??  Slayer
You guys are all wrong!!! It's obviously a Flux Capacitor!!!!
Correct, used in emergencies to fire an inverse tachyon pulse through the main deflector array. It destabilises the surrounding subspace field and prevents a warp core breach.
